I just had a discussion with a work college about how to organize a features routing configuration.

We discussed two approaches. 

**Approach 1: separate routing module** 

The 1st approach is to create a seperate `feature-a-routing.module.ts` which contains all routing stuff and import it in the `FeatureAModule`:
```
// feature-a-routing.module.ts
const routes: Routes = [
    {
        path: &#39;/&#39;,
        component: HelloComponent,
    }
];

@NgModule({
    imports: [RouterModule.forChild(routes)],
    exports: [RouterModule]
})
export class FeatureARoutingModule {}
```
```
// feature-a.module.ts
@NgModule({
    declarations: [
        HelloComponent,
        NeugeschaeftContainerComponent,
        ProduktauswahlNeugeschaeftComponent
    ],
    providers: [],
    imports: [CommonModule, FeatureARoutingModule]
})
export class FeatureAModule {}
```
**Approach 2: separate routes constant**

The 2nd approach is to only define the `routes`constant in a separate file:
```
// feature-a-routes.ts
export const featureARoutes: Routes = [
    {
        path: &#39;/&#39;,
        component: HelloComponent,
    }
];
```
```
// feature-a.module.ts
@NgModule({
    declarations: [
        HelloComponent,
        NeugeschaeftContainerComponent,
        ProduktauswahlNeugeschaeftComponent
    ],
    providers: [],
    imports: [CommonModule, RouterModule.forChild(featureARoutes)]
})
export class FeatureAModule {}
```


**Discussion**

The 1st approach seems to have a better separation of concerns. Which is the only difference I see.
Are there any other benefits of this 1st approach maybe concerning testing, optimization or are there even caveats?
And what would be the benefits of the 2nd approach?

